---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidenote from '../../components/Sidenote.astro';
import Sparkline from '../../components/Sparkline.astro';
---

<Base title="Infinite Sales Cycle">
  <article>
    <h1>Infinite Sales Cycle</h1>
    <p class="subtitle" style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-style: italic; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
      Sales never stops. Every output feeds the next input.
    </p>

    <h2>The Model</h2>

    <p>
      Most solopreneurs treat sales as a campaign: launch, push, rest, repeat. This creates
      boom-bust cycles and morning confusion.
      <Sidenote id="boom-bust">
        The campaign model works for products with a launch date. Education products —
        cohorts, communities, coaching — need continuous visibility. The funnel is always on.
      </Sidenote>
    </p>

    <p>The infinite cycle treats every action as both delivery and lead generation:</p>

    <pre><code>Create → Publish → Engage → Convert → Deliver → Document → Create
  ↑                                                           |
  └───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘</code></pre>

    <h2>Each Step Feeds the Next</h2>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th><th>Sales Output</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Create</strong></td><td>Build a skill, write a post</td><td>Portfolio piece</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Publish</strong></td><td>Share on LinkedIn/YouTube</td><td>Visibility</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Engage</strong></td><td>Reply to comments, DMs</td><td>Relationship</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Convert</strong></td><td>Offer help, invite to lab</td><td>Lead → Sale</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Deliver</strong></td><td>Run the lab/community</td><td>Case study material</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Document</strong></td><td>Record results, testimonials</td><td>Social proof</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Revenue Targets — Berlin 2026</h2>

    <p>For a solo educator in Berlin, baseline sustainability:</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Item</th><th>Monthly</th><th></th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Living costs Berlin</td>
          <td>~€2,500</td>
          <td><Sparkline data={[2200, 2300, 2350, 2400, 2450, 2500]} type="line" color="#555" /></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Tools &amp; subscriptions</td>
          <td>~€300</td>
          <td></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Tax reserve (30%)</td>
          <td>~€1,200</td>
          <td></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Minimum revenue</strong></td>
          <td><strong>~€4,000</strong></td>
          <td></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Comfortable target</strong></td>
          <td><strong>~€7,000</strong></td>
          <td><Sparkline data={[3, 3.5, 4, 5, 5.5, 6, 7]} type="area" color="#059669" /></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>
      This means: 1 cohort (6–8 people × €500–800) per quarter + community revenue.
      <Sidenote id="pricing">
        Western market pricing for comparable cohort-based AI training ranges
        €800–2,500. Current Russian-market pricing of €500–800 has room to grow
        for English-language cohorts.
      </Sidenote>
    </p>

    <h2>Anti-Pattern</h2>

    <p>
      Building 50 skills (Create) without promoting them (Publish/Engage).
      The daily dashboard always includes items from at least 2 different cycle stages
      to prevent this trap.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
